The paper uses game theory to analyze the behavior of agents in a network game, which suggests that it belongs to the cs.GT (Game Theory) sub-category. The paper also focuses on crowd sensing social systems, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category. The paper also discusses the behavior of individuals in a network, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.SOC (Social and Behavioral Sciences) sub-category. The paper also discusses the implications of the results on designing effective recruitment mechanisms, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.CYBER (Cybersecurity and Privacy) sub-category. Finally, the paper uses mathematical expressions to derive the Nash equilibrium efforts put in by the agents, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category.
